# Comprehensive Guide to C++ Concepts

This guide aims to provide an extensive, specific, and detailed explanation and application of various C++ concepts. We'll cover topics from basic objects to file I/O, including linked lists, vectors, and multidimensional arrays. This guide is divided into units, each focusing on a specific area of C++ programming.

## Unit 3 a: Basic Objects (Structs), Assignment of Objects, . and -> Operators, Use of getline(), Checking an Input Stream for Failure, and Using C++ String Class

### Basic Objects (Structs)

In C++, a struct is a composite data type that groups together variables of different types, creating a single object. Structs are similar to classes, except that class members are private by default, while struct members are public by default.

```cpp
struct Point {
    int x, y;
};
```

### Assignment of Objects

Object assignment in C++ copies the values of the data members from one object to another.

```cpp
Point p1, p2;
p1.x = 1;
p1.y = 2;

p2 = p1; // Assigns the values of p1 to p2
```

### . and -> Operators

The `.` operator is used to access the members of an object when the object is being referred to directly. The `->` operator is used to access the members of a pointer to an object.

```cpp
Point p;
p.x = 1;
p.y = 2;

Point* pp = &p;
pp->x = 3;
pp->y = 4;
```

### Use of getline()

The `getline()` function reads a line from an input stream into a string object.

```cpp
std::string line;
std::getline(std::cin, line);
```

### Checking an Input Stream for Failure

After reading input from a stream, you can check the state of the stream to see if the operation failed.

```cpp
std::string line;
std::getline(std::cin, line);
if (std::cin.fail()) {
    std::cout << "Input failed\n";
    std::cin.clear(); // Clear the error state
    std::cin.ignore(std::numeric_limits<std::streamsize>::max(), '\n'); // Discard the input
}
```

### Using C++ String Class

The `std::string` class provides a powerful and flexible way to work with text in C++.

```cpp
std::string str = "Hello, World!";
str.substr(7, 5); // "World"
str.replace(0, 6, "Hola"); // "Hola, World!"
```

## Unit 3 b: Defining Your Own Classes, Public vs. Private, Constructors and Destructors, and Splitting Your Class into Files

### Defining Your Own Classes

Classes are used to encapsulate data and functions that operate on that data into a single unit.

```cpp
class Person {
public:
    std::string name;
    int age;

    void sayHello() {
        std::cout << "Hello, I'm " << name << ".\n";
    }
};
```

### Public vs. Private

Public members can be accessed from outside the class, while private members are only accessible within the class itself.

```cpp
class Person {
private:
    std::string name;
    int age;

public:
    void setName(const std::string& newName) {
        name = newName;
    }

    void sayHello() {
        std::cout << "Hello, I'm " << name << ".\n";
    }
};
```

### Constructors and Destructors

Constructors are special member functions that are called when an object is created, while destructors are called when an object is destroyed.

```cpp
class Person {
public:
    std::string name;
    int age;

    Person(const std::string& newName, int newAge) {
        name = newName;
        age = newAge;
    }

    ~Person() {
        std::cout << "Bye, I'm " << name << ".\n";
    }
};
```

### Splitting Your Class into Files

To split a large class into multiple files, define the class in a header file and implement the member functions in a corresponding source file.

```hpp
// person.hpp
#ifndef PERSON_HPP
#define PERSON_HPP

class Person {
public:
    std::string name;
    int age;

    Person(const std::string& newName, int newAge);

    void sayHello();
};

#endif
```

```cpp
// person.cpp
#include "person.hpp"
#include <iostream>

Person::Person(const std::string& newName, int newAge) : name(newName), age(newAge) {
    // Constructor
}

void Person::sayHello() {
    std::cout << "Hello, I'm " << name << ".\n";
}
```

## Unit 4 a: Linked Lists, Implementing Basic Operations, and Efficiency

### Linked Lists

A linked list is a linear data structure where each element contains a value and a reference to the next element in the list.

```cpp
struct Node {
    int data;
    Node* next;
};

class LinkedList {
private:
    Node* head;

public:
    LinkedList() : head(nullptr) {}

    void pushFront(int value) {
        Node* newNode = new Node;
        newNode->data = value;
        newNode->next = head;
        head = newNode;
    }

    void popFront() {
        if (head) {
            Node* temp = head;
            head = head->next;
            delete temp;
        }
    }

    // Other operations...
};
```

### Efficiency of Various Operations

- Push: O(1)
- Pop from front: O(1)
- Accessing an element: O(n)
- Searching for an element: O(n)

### Pros and Cons Compared to Arrays

- Pros:
  - Dynamic size
  - Insertions and deletions are efficient at the beginning (O(1))

- Cons:
  - Accessing an element is less efficient (O(n))
  - Memory is not stored contiguously

## Unit 4 b: vector<T> and deque<T> Basic Operations and Efficiency

### vector<T>

`vector<T>` is a dynamic array that can grow and shrink at run time.

- Push back: O(1) amortized
- Pop back: O(1)
- Accessing an element: O(1)
- Searching for an element: O(n)

### deque<T>

`deque<T>` is a double-ended queue that allows efficient insertions and deletions at both ends.

- Push back/front: O(1) amortized
- Pop back/front: O(1)
- Accessing an element: O(1)
